land":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Self","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Sa(h)ulf</i> (Old English <i>Sǣwulf</i>, from <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’).","North German: nickname from Low German <i>self</i> ‘self’ for a self-important person."],"variants":[{"name":"Selph","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Self  ."]},{"name":"Selfe","meanings":["English: variant of   Self  ."]},{"name":"Silverstone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aron, Emanuel, Herschel.","English: habitational name from Silverstone (Northamptonshire), probably from the Old English personal name <i>Sigewulf</i> (genitive <i>Sigewulfes</i>) or <i>Sǣwulf</i> (genitive <i>Sǣwulfes</i>; see   Self  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Silberstein  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":89,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Self was born about 1480, in England. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs William Self."},"et":{"about 1480–":"umbes 1480–Surnud","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1485":"1485","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","England":"England","Naseby, Northhamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1480–":"noin 1480–Kuollut","1485–Female":"1485–Kuollut","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1480–Male":"1480–Kuollut","about 1480":"noin 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1485":"1485","1571":"1571","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","England":"England","Naseby, Northhamptonshire, England":"Naseby, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1480–":"environ 1480–Décédé","1485–Female":"1485–Décédée","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1480–Male":"1480–Décédé","about 1480":"environ 1480","1569